# PAI Task System — Requirements Clarification

> Pre-build clarification doc. Staff-solutions-architect lens. No code yet. Goal: surface every meaningful design decision before the ISA is written.

## 1. Summary of understanding

Nick wants a personal task system built on top of PAI that replaces his paper notebook for everything the notebook can't do well (search, cross-project context, agent review, mobile capture, persistence across days), while preserving the things the notebook does best (zero-friction capture, spatial scan, fast reordering, satisfying "done" gesture). It needs: lightweight capture, allocation to project/life-area, prioritisation, a today-view that slots items into time blocks (e.g. A/B/C 09:00 to 11:00; D/E/F 13:00 to 15:00), a backlog, per-item notes, and a "personal assistant" agent that periodically reviews the list with him (is this done? still relevant? what changed?) and surfaces gaps and forgotten items. He flagged a possible GitHub-backed implementation as worth considering. The system is for Nick alone, multi-front (career pivot, two SaaS products, two volunteer leadership roles, personal admin), and needs a great UI on both web and mobile.

## 2. Working name

Sticking with "PAI Task System" loses the chance to give the thing a personality. Three candidates:

| Name | Pitch | Cost |
|------|-------|------|
| **Tasks** | Honest, terse, no ego. Sits next to Pulse, Telos in the PAI lexicon. | Generic; SEO-poor inside the PAI codebase if you ever google for it. |
| **Inkwell** | Pays direct tribute to the notebook it is replacing. Carries the metaphor through the UI (pages, ink, margin notes). | Twee risk if not held tightly. |
| **Daily** | Names the dominant verb: pull from the pool, decide on today. | Underplays the backlog, agent-review, and cross-project work. |

**Recommendation:** ship as `Tasks` internally and brand the UI as "Inkwell" if you want the notebook callback. Decide later.

## 3. Key assumptions

1. **Single-user.** No shared lists, no delegation to a partner or assistant other than the agent. If joint-finance-style sharing comes later, it is v2+.
2. **Local-first.** Source of truth lives on Nick's machine (file-backed markdown or local Postgres), not in a cloud SaaS. The mobile surface syncs to local-first.
3. **Tasks are not calendar events.** A scheduled block on a today-view is not the same object as a Google Calendar event. We may sync but the task ledger is canonical.
4. **The agent is a real participant.** Not a UI nicety. It writes to the ledger, asks questions through Pulse or Telegram or a chat surface, and Nick answers in natural language.
5. **PAI is the OS.** Auth, secrets, voice, and notifications go through the PAI stack (Pulse 31337, ElevenLabs voice, Telegram, iMessage). No new auth system.
6. **Stack defaults.** bun + TypeScript, Postgres if relational store is used, Hono for any API, Next.js + shadcn/ui for the UI, PWA for mobile. No Python.
7. **Project/area taxonomy is finite and known.** Career, AccessBuddy, LIMSOC, LifesaverOnCall, LSV Comms, SMLSC, Personal, PAI Tooling, Life OS Console. Reuse the PROJECTS.md registry rather than reinvent.
8. **"Time block" granularity is hours, not minutes.** Nick's scheduling examples (9 to 11, 1 to 3) imply human-sized blocks, not pomodoro precision. If wrong, ledger granularity changes.
9. **No team review surface.** No PR, no stakeholder dashboard. The agent is the only reviewer.
10. **Capture must work when offline and when the laptop is closed.** Mobile and CLI capture both must work without the web app being open.

If any of these is wrong, flag it and the architecture pivots.

## 4. Mental model & metaphor

Three credible metaphors:

| Metaphor | Strengths | Weaknesses for Nick |
|----------|-----------|---------------------|
| **Ticketing system** (Linear, GitHub Issues, Jira) | Project allocation, prioritisation, comments, status lifecycle, agent automation all native. | Heavy ceremony per item; capture friction higher than a notebook line. Today-scheduling is awkward. |
| **Outliner + day plan** (Things 3, OmniFocus, Logseq) | Capture is fast; today-view first-class; project sidebar is natural. | Cross-project review and agent integration weaker; backlog hygiene drifts. |
| **Notebook + day page** (Roam-style, daily notes) | Closest to the paper notebook. Spatial. Forgiving. | Structured queries (priority, area, "what is overdue") get harder. Agent needs structure to act on. |

**Recommendation: Outliner + day plan with ticket-style metadata behind the scenes.** Capture is a single line, dropped onto a daily inbox or quick-add. The item gets project/area/priority/notes lazily, either by the user or the agent. The today-view is its own surface with time blocks. The backlog is just "everything not on a today-view yet." This beats the notebook on search, agent review, and cross-project visibility while keeping capture latency under a second.

The notebook constraint is the constant against which every UI decision gets measured. If a screen requires more than one tap or keystroke to capture a thought, it loses against the notebook and Nick will quietly go back to paper.

## 5. Preliminary architecture sketch

### 5.1 Storage options

| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |
|--------|-------------|------|------|
| **A. File-backed markdown** in `~/.claude/PAI/MEMORY/TASKS/` | One markdown file per task or per day, frontmatter for structured fields. | Native to PAI memory pattern. Survives any tool failure. Hand-editable. Git-friendly. | Queries (top priority items across projects) require an index. Mobile editing is harder. |
| **B. Local Postgres** | Tasks table, relations to projects/areas. | Fast queries, clean joins, transactional. | Yet another service to run. Backups become Nick's problem. Less hand-editable. |
| **C. GitHub Issues + Projects** | One repo per area; GitHub Projects v2 board for the today-view. | Free hosting, mobile app exists, agent can post comments, audit log free. | Capture latency is higher (GitHub network roundtrip). Notebook-replacement test fails. Sensitive data leaves the laptop. Rate limits on the agent. |
| **D. Hybrid: file-backed markdown + SQLite read-model** | Markdown is canonical; SQLite is rebuilt on change. | Best of both — durable, queryable, agent-friendly. | One more moving piece. |

**Recommendation: D (markdown canonical + SQLite read-model).** SQLite over Postgres because this is single-user and we want it dead simple. GitHub is out for capture-latency and privacy reasons but could be a mirror for mobile review.

### 5.2 Data model (first cut)

```
Task
  id              ulid
  title           text (one-liner, the notebook line)
  body            text (markdown notes, optional)
  project         enum from PROJECTS registry (nullable; "inbox" if unassigned)
  area            enum (Career, Health, Money, Relationships, Creative, Civic, Tooling) (optional)
  status          enum (inbox, backlog, today, doing, done, dropped, snoozed)
  priority        enum (P0 must-do-today, P1 important, P2 normal, P3 someday)
  created_at      timestamp
  updated_at      timestamp
  due             date (optional)
  estimate_min    int (optional)
  energy          enum (deep, shallow, errand) (optional)
  blocks          [task_id]
  blocked_by      [task_id]

DayPlan
  date            date
  blocks          [TimeBlock]

TimeBlock
  start           time
  end             time
  task_ids        [task_id]
  label           text (optional, e.g. "deep work — LIMSOC")

AgentTouch
  task_id         task_id
  timestamp       timestamp
  question        text
  response        text
  outcome         enum (still_relevant, dropped, edited, rescheduled, completed)
```

Status lifecycle: `inbox → backlog → today → doing → done`, with branches to `dropped` and `snoozed` at any point.

### 5.3 Surfaces

| Surface | Purpose | Priority |
|---------|---------|----------|
| **CLI quick-add** (`tasks add "..."`) | Sub-second capture from terminal. | P0 |
| **Web app** (Next.js, localhost or LAN) | Primary review and scheduling UI. | P0 |
| **Mobile PWA** | Capture and review from phone. iOS install via add-to-home. | P0 |
| **Pulse widget** | "What's on today?" tile on the Life Dashboard. | P1 |
| **Telegram/iMessage bot** | Capture from anywhere by message; agent check-ins arrive here. | P1 |
| **Voice capture** | "Jarvis, add: …" via ElevenLabs flow. | P2 |
| **Daily markdown export** | One file per day in OneDrive, for the notebook-replacement feel. | P2 |

### 5.4 Agent integration

A scheduled PAI agent (e.g. `task-orchestrator`) runs at chosen cadences:

- **Morning** (08:00): proposes a today-view from priority + estimate + calendar gaps.
- **Midday** (13:00): "What got done from the morning block? Anything blocked?"
- **Evening** (18:00): closes the day, moves unfinished work to tomorrow's inbox or backlog.
- **Weekly** (Sunday): backlog hygiene — flags stale items, items with no project, items repeated across days.
- **Ad hoc**: gap-spotting against PROJECTS.md and CHALLENGES.md — "you said you would draft the SMLSC paper this week, no task captured."

The agent never silently mutates. Every proposed edit goes through Pulse or Telegram as a one-tap accept/reject.

### 5.5 GitHub-backed alternative — should we?

Considered seriously. Verdict: **no for the primary store**, **yes as a one-way mirror** if Nick wants a mobile review surface for free. Reasons:

- Capture latency on GitHub Issues is 300 to 1500ms — worse than paper, worse than a local CLI. The notebook test fails immediately.
- Sensitive content (e.g. career-pivot notes, LIMSOC SME details) should not leave the laptop without a deliberate choice.
- GitHub Projects v2 is excellent for engineering teams but heavy for a single user juggling 9 fronts.
- Agent automation against GitHub burns API quota and adds latency where local is free.

If Nick wants the GitHub mobile app for review, mirror selected projects out, do not push capture in.

## 6. Critical clarifying questions, grouped and prioritised

### 6.1 Capture UX (the most load-bearing decisions)

1. **Primary capture surface in the moment of "I just thought of a thing"?**  Options: (a) CLI from any terminal tab, (b) Telegram message to Jarvis, (c) iMessage to Jarvis, (d) PWA "+" button, (e) all of the above with one canonical sync. *Recommendation: all of the above. Confirm.*
2. **Sub-second target for capture: real or aspirational?** If Nick wants sub-second, the laptop must already be unlocked and the terminal already open. Are we OK with "30 seconds when phone is in pocket" as the realistic target?
3. **One field on capture, or three?** "Title only and figure the rest out later" vs "title + project + priority required up front." The notebook is one field. *Recommendation: title only, defer everything else.*
4. **Voice capture in v1, or v2?** Voice is the only sub-second mobile capture. Worth building first?
5. **Should the agent auto-classify** project and area from the title text? It can guess; Nick approves with one tap.

### 6.2 Today-view and scheduling

6. **Are time blocks a planning artefact or a tracking artefact?** Planning = "I intend to do A/B/C from 9 to 11." Tracking = "I did A/B/C from 9 to 11." Different data model implications.
7. **Do blocks need to align with the calendar?** Should the today-view read Google Calendar to know when meetings are, and slot blocks into the gaps?
8. **Default block length?** 90 min, 120 min, or "no default — Nick draws them"?
9. **What happens to a task that wasn't finished in its block?** Auto-roll to next block, auto-roll to tomorrow, or ask?
10. **Today-view persists how?** As an immutable "this is what I planned" snapshot, or always the live state?

### 6.3 Project and area model

11. **Use existing PROJECTS.md registry** as the source of truth for the project list, or maintain a separate list inside Tasks?  *Recommendation: read from PROJECTS.md, add an internal "inbox" and "personal" if missing.*
12. **Is "area" needed in addition to "project"?** Areas (Career, Health, Money, Relationships, Creative, Civic) come from Telos and IDEAL_STATE. Projects are concrete. Both, or just projects?
13. **Multiple projects per task?** Yes/no.
14. **Tags in addition to project/area?** Free tags risk taxonomy drift but help search.

### 6.4 Priority model

15. **Priority levels: P0/P1/P2/P3, or just "today vs not today"?** The latter is closer to the notebook. The former gives the agent something to sort by.
16. **Auto-decay priority** if a task has been P1 for 14 days and never done? Forces a real decision.

### 6.5 Agent behaviour (this is the differentiator from any off-the-shelf tool)

17. **Check-in cadence and surface?** Morning/midday/evening as proposed, or different? On which surface — Pulse widget, Telegram message, iMessage, or all?
18. **Can the agent close tasks unilaterally?** Or must Nick confirm every state change?
19. **Gap-spotting scope.** Should the agent read CHALLENGES.md, GOALS.md, project ISAs, and recent commit history to spot uncaptured work? *Recommendation: yes, weekly.*
20. **Agent "voice" — Jarvis, or a dedicated task-agent with a distinct personality?**
21. **Bothered threshold.** How often is "too often"? Hard cap of N pings/day, or learn from Nick's response rate?
22. **What does the agent do with a task that has been in backlog for 30+ days untouched?** Auto-drop with notice, ask, or leave alone?

### 6.6 Sync and offline

23. **Source of truth lives where?** Local laptop (canonical) + mobile is read-mostly with offline capture queue, or both equal and conflict-resolve on sync?
24. **Sync mechanism.** Tailscale + REST endpoint, iCloud Drive file sync, Git auto-commit, or a hosted endpoint (Cloudflare Worker + Tunnel)?  *Recommendation: Tailscale + local API + offline queue on mobile.*
25. **Conflict resolution rules** when mobile and desktop both edited the same task offline.

### 6.7 Storage and persistence

26. **Markdown canonical + SQLite read-model** vs Postgres-only. Earlier recommendation: markdown canonical. Confirm.
27. **One file per task** or **one file per day**?
28. **Where on disk?** `~/.claude/PAI/MEMORY/TASKS/` vs `~/OneDrive/...`. OneDrive gives free cross-device backup but the Linux rclone 12h cache (per your existing memory note) becomes a sync hazard.
29. **Backups.** Nightly snapshot to where?

### 6.8 Mobile

30. **PWA install path acceptable** (add to home screen on iOS Safari), or native iOS shell required for capture to be fast enough?
31. **Mobile push notifications** for agent check-ins — via Telegram (free) or APNs (build cost)?

### 6.9 Pulse integration

32. **What lives on Pulse?** A "today" widget (top 3 items, current block), a "captured this week" counter, an "agent has questions" tile? Pick the 2 most useful.

### 6.10 Reporting and review

33. **Weekly review surface.** Does Nick want a "what got done, what slid" view on Sunday? Generated by agent and posted where?
34. **Telos linkage.** Should tasks roll up to GOALS.md so progress is visible? If yes, manual tag or agent-inferred?

### 6.11 Integration with existing PAI artefacts

35. **Should completed tasks become LEARNING.md / KNOWLEDGE.md entries** when significant? Or are tasks ephemeral and Telos owns the long memory?
36. **CHALLENGES.md and PROBLEMS.md feed.** Should "P0: solve X" turn into auto-generated breakdown tasks the agent proposes?

### 6.12 Auth and security

37. **Anyone other than Nick ever opens this UI?** If no, no auth on localhost. If maybe-mobile-on-LAN, need a minimal auth (PAI cred or magic-link).
38. **Sensitivity of content.** Are career-pivot notes, financial tasks, or LSV comms tasks in scope? If yes, no cloud SaaS for storage.

### 6.13 Capture hygiene

39. **Item lifespan.** Default snooze, default drop after N days unreviewed?
40. **Recurring tasks.** Daily/weekly/monthly recurrences in v1, or v2?

### 6.14 Calendar integration

41. **Google Calendar read?** To know meeting gaps.
42. **Google Calendar write?** Push the day's blocks back as events.

## 7. Open trade-offs needing Nick's call

| Decision | Option A | Option B | Cost of getting it wrong |
|----------|----------|----------|--------------------------|
| **Canonical store** | Markdown files | Local Postgres | A: harder structured queries. B: harder hand-edit and harder PAI memory consistency. |
| **Mobile** | PWA-only | Native shell | A: capture latency on iOS slightly worse. B: build cost ~5x, App Store friction. |
| **Agent autonomy** | Propose-and-confirm | Auto-close on signals | A: more pings. B: trust collapses if the agent gets one closure wrong. |
| **Calendar coupling** | Tasks own time blocks; calendar is read-only context | Time blocks are written to calendar | A: calendar stays uncluttered. B: phone calendar alerts fire for your own plan. |
| **Today-view immutability** | Snapshot at 09:00 | Live-mutating | A: post-hoc review honest. B: today reflects reality. |
| **GitHub mirror** | None | One-way mirror of selected projects | A: zero mobile review surface for free. B: extra moving piece. |

## 8. Suggested MVP scope

**Goal: beat the notebook on capture latency + cross-day persistence + agent review, within 2 to 3 weekends of build.**

In:
- CLI quick-add (`tasks add "..."`) writing markdown to `~/.claude/PAI/MEMORY/TASKS/`
- SQLite read-model built on file change
- Web app (Next.js + shadcn/ui) with three views: Inbox, Today, Backlog
- Drag-drop between Inbox/Backlog/Today (or keyboard shortcuts)
- Per-item notes (markdown body)
- Project allocation from a fixed list (read from PROJECTS.md)
- Priority field (P0/P1/P2/P3)
- A daily agent check-in via Telegram at 17:00 — "what got done; what rolls"

Out (v1.0 or later):
- Mobile PWA
- Time-block scheduling on today-view (manual list in MVP, blocks in v1.0)
- Voice capture
- Calendar read
- Auto-classification by agent
- Pulse widget
- Recurring tasks
- Telos rollup

Explicit cut line: **if it doesn't beat the notebook in 3 weeks, kill the project and keep the notebook.**

## 9. Risks

| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|------|------------|--------|------------|
| Capture latency loses against the notebook | High | Project dies | CLI quick-add ships first, measured against stopwatch. |
| Agent becomes noisy and gets muted | Medium | Differentiator dies | Hard cap on pings, response-rate adaptive cadence, one-touch "shut up today". |
| Backlog grows to 500+ items | High over 6 months | Tool feels heavy | Aggressive default-drop after 60 days, weekly hygiene by agent. |
| Mobile capture never gets built and Nick goes back to notebook for "on the go" thoughts | Medium | Hybrid system, neither wins | PWA in v1.0, voice in v1.1. |
| Markdown + SQLite drift | Low | Data integrity | Markdown is canonical; SQLite always rebuildable from files. |
| Sensitive content accidentally synced to GitHub mirror | Low | Privacy | Allowlist for mirrored projects, never an opt-out. |
| Project bikeshed: 3 weeks of taxonomy debates, no usable tool | Medium | Time sink | MVP cut line is brutal. |

